reviewText: After first being introduced to Larry the Cable Guy via the infamously hilarious Blue Collar Comedy Tour film, I was eager to see how this backwoods redneck would do all on his own.  Is his success and humor due in part to the guys that he traveled with in this film, or would this one night of laughs prove to be a miscalculation on Larry's part.  Well, in my humble opinion, it was not his best outing to date.Something enjoyable about his routine on the Blue Collar Comedy DVD is that it is a short, quick-fire routine showcasing some of his talents.  Honestly, if you read my reviews about the two Blue Collar films than you will see that I genuinely found myself laughing at Larry the longest.  His humor seemed raw and perhaps a bit different than what the other three performers had in mind.  He was like the black sheep in these films, yet when given the opportunity to stand on his own, he does not come out a shining star.The first issue that I had with this routine was the repetitive nature of his jokes.  I realize that his catch phrase is "Git-R-Done", but I do not believe that one should gather laughter from the audience by telling a joke that bombs, but creates a panic when he yells the phrase "Git-R-Done".  It ruined his image to me and showed me that he wasn't willing to pick up the pieces and move ahead, but instead throw in a phrase that had nothing to do with the joke to cover his face.  It was shameful.  Then, to follow suit, he does it again.  He uses more than just the "Git-R-Done" phrase to cover up uneventful jokes like his trademark apology and impression of someone suffering from mental retardation.  HA, yep that normally gets a laugh from the audience making fun of others misfortunes ... geez.  Literally, if you wanted to you could count the actual "jokes" on one hand in this film due to most of it being nothing more than filler and repetitive humor to bring the audience back from slumber.So, perhaps you can ignore the same joke told over and over and over again, but can you deal with Larry quite possibly criticizing every misfortune that has befallen the people of this great land?  While I am a Democrat, I love to keep an open mind.  I knew Larry was going to be very Southern, very opinionated, but midway during his show (when you could tell he was loosing the audience) I believed him just to be saying things that would gather the attention back to him on stage.  There were moments where the words coming from his mouth nearly made me turn the television off.  The bits about the workers learning English made me want to scream out loud.  I wonder how many languages Larry knows?  It had pushed the envelope too far, and when he didn't think that it went far enough, his calculations would be to throw in a poop joke for even bigger laughter.  If farting didn't exist, Larry the Cable Guy would be out of luck.His comments tried to be jokes, but just came out racist and fearful of the audience that chose to listen.  While I was ready for anything, Larry the Cable Guy provided nothing.  His caged humor on the Blue Collar Comedy Tour was hysterical, but when you open the cage door and let him run free he does not have the self-control or ability complete his sentences and thoughts.  Repetition and crassy, unfunny, childish bathroom humor does not excuse you from telling good jokes.  Apparently, Larry thought otherwise.Overall, I was not impressed.  I was expecting so much from this mock redneck that this comedy album produced a reverse result.  I felt that he was trying to be dicey or racy, but instead (coupled with his repetition and bathroom charm) it actually turned out to be amateur hour at the local bar.  Larry needs new material and a stronger ability to time his "Git-R-Done" phrase.  With this in mind, he may return as a very funny comedian, but as of now, I just see him as a petty joke pusher for the clinically redneck.  How sad!Grade: ** out of *****
summary: Cable Guy left nothing but static...

reviewText: If you're a wuss and get easily offended, stay away from this DVD, but if you're not a politically correct girley man as my California Governor Ahnold would say (and that applies to both sexes), you'll laugh until you cry.Larry the Cable Guy is the redneck Don Rickles, and is an equal opportunity insulter. His is also some of the most inventive stand-up comedy I've heard.I normally won't tolerate bad language and bathroom humor, because it is usually said as the main reason to make one laugh, for some sort of "shock value"; Larry the Cable Guy says gross toilet humor as part of the story, and it's the story that's funny, not just the way it's said.Some stories are outrageous, but there are many things out of everyday life...Larry ponders whether it's "Pet Smart" or Pets Mart" (I've often had the same thing run through my head) and in telling us of Rosie O'Donnell's  confrontation with NRA member Tom Selleck, he says something I really like: "if guns kill people, I can blame misspelled words on my pencil".The show, which was filmed at The State Theatre in Kalamazoo, Michigan, on October 30th, 2003, is 66 minutes long, and the DVD extras include a "gallery", and a segment that is about 4 minutes long of "Bathroom Humor", actually filmed in a public restroom, with Larry in a stall.The show takes a dip in the middle when he's talking about edible britches, but picks up again and Bubli Bubli's letter is a riot, and the Christmas song finale priceless. The last one had me roaring.Someday Larry the Cable Guy is going to be sued. Not for insulting someone with a defect, but for making someone choke to death with laughter. Git-R-Done Larry !

reviewText: Larry the Cable Guy and his southern redneck stand-up comedy shtick is very funny, mostly.  This DVD features Larry in a 66-minute stand-up monologue, which is much edgier and little more vulgar in parts than his act in The Blue Collar Comedy Tour.  There's a lot of juvenile bathroom humor - especially about flatulence.  And Larry pokes a lot of fun at people with disabilities.  If you are easily offended by these things this video is not for you!  Myself, I found it most of it laugh out loud funny although there are some moments that aren't so funny.  Also, I'd already seen some the material in the Blue Collar Comedy Tour videos.The extra features were stupid frankly.  There's a short skit called "Bathroom Humor" which was not funny and then a bunch of silly pictures of Larry.But overall I would give this DVD a thumbs up because it makes you laugh and is something you can watch multiple times and still enjoy it.

reviewText: Yes it is...I don't care who you are, despite that fact that Larry is above all else rude and crude he is freaking hillarious.  Poking fun at everything from religion to homosexuality to masturbating and gross body noises Larry really has a vast array of bathroom humor to run with, but it's when he's forgotten his body functions and picks up on 'other' things that he really shines, like his pigmi adopted son and his over-the-top yet completly HILLARIOUS letter from him.  Or his take on contemperary Christmas jingles.  Larry may offend many, but taken in context he's just having fun.  Larry says many racist, sexist and politically incorect things, but he never really comes off like he believes most of what he's saying and thats what I appreciate about him.  He can have fun and he can poke fun (mostly at the obvious) but he never comes across like a racist or a sexist, just as a guy who enjoys a good laugh.  His opinion on the whole 'grooming' of the nether-regions is a riot, and when he talks about tucking mister happy between his legs for kicks it'll have you rolling.  I don't care who you are, this DVD is FUNNY!

reviewText: Is Larry an actual redneck, or is it all really a joke inside "Larry's" mind?  I sometimes think that Dan Whitney (Larry's real name) knows what he's doing.  I think he is actually making a huge joke out of the rednecks who are totally in love with him.  He is openly mocking them, and when they might get a tad uncomfortable, but then he'll drop a politically incorrect joke into the routine, and they love him again.  Dan/Larry started out as a "normal" comedian (there's footage of him on youtube before his Larry incarnation), and wasn't really getting anywhere with that.  So he became a redneck, and is a multi-millionare now.  But all his redneck fans think of Larry as a "regular guy", despite the fact that Larry lives in one of those fancy houses that rednecks think only NYCers live in (for the record, NYCers don't all live in fancy houses.  There's a lot of working class people in NYC who live in regular houses and regular apartments).  So Larry is taking advantage of illiterate, easily amused rednecks.  Just put on a flannel shirt, fart, wear a Confederate flag, and say you hate liberals, then fleece the rednecks!  I don't think Larry really has a redneck mentality (even though he's originally from Nebraska, so he has some hillbilly cred, so to speak).  I think he's just making a ton of money off of easily amused people.
summary: Larry, in reality, hates rednecks, but he loves their money...

reviewText: this man may very well be the grand interpreter of the mass consciousness of the dumb half of the united states. on top of that, it's brutally unfunny. his set on the blue collar comedy tour seems mercifully short and might as well be "citizen kane" compared to this gala of idiocy. comedy this dangerously insipid, brain-dead, and not to mention totally unfunny should be outlawed. no one is as dumb as larry the cable guy professes to be; true. however, everyone i know who comes close votes republican. what does that mean? who cares. now click "no" and tell me my review wasn't helpful. sorry, but if you like larry the cable guy in the first place i think you're most likely beyond help.all told, if you're into the mean-spirited rantings of an inbred jackass on the mentally challenged, gloriously naive and simplistic views on politics, ignorant critiques of immigrants, or banal and crude sexist humor then be my guest and lose a few brain cells while you're at it. it's not like you were using them anyway. this guy should have headlined the republican national convention; he would have killed.and before you call me a sissy or a "girly man" for not finding this dolt hilarious like california cretin already did, i can definately deal with gay bashing and racist humor. i love south park, family guy, and chappelle's show; all of which have employed all of those comedic elements in one way or another. however, those shows are satiric in nature and avoid rolling in their own molasses-thick vitriol, unlike ol' larry. i've lived in the south all my life and his hometown is a day trip away...as such i think i can offer my opinion with much more authenticity.my review of the blue collar comedy tour goes much deeper into why i can't stand this guy.
summary: the lowest valley on the landscape of stand-up

reviewText: Git-r-done is a nonstop display of a brilliant comedic genius known as Larry the cable guy. Larry never ceases to pull off witty punchlines that at first go over your head, but end up doubling you over with laughter. His preformance will definitely torque your brain, so be prepared. There are a couple instances where Larry goes a little too far and really flexes his mental might leaving you feeling fragile and insecure. One such occurance is his bit about grandma farting like a machine gun. I was left very confused and uncertain of myself until it dawned on me that Larry was just messing with me because we all know girls don't fart, they don't even have buttholes. He then tries to pull a fast one when he proclaims he never works out EVER. Unless you are an idiot, you know you can't look like him without a strict training regiment, nice try Larry. He finally sounds off with an insightful and powerful anti-Hillary Clinton piece. This was the icing on the cake for me because when I think of intelligent political commentary, I think Larry the cable guy!!!!!

reviewText: For giving the rednecks of america a catchphrase to plaster on their pickups, windows, t-shirts and mobile homes. It's actually become a part of speech down there to sub in for anything else.Joe Bob- How ya doinChet- Purty good, what ya doin todayJoe Bob- Cuttin the lawn on my John DeereChet- GIT R DONE!!That's high level conversation and our whole curling team says it to each other before we hit the ice now. I'm in a curling club and as with everything else I do, I'm really good at it. I sweep like a maid on crack and get the round thing in the circle it's supposed to go in. As I'm sweeping, the rest of the team yells Git r done. That motivates me to do even better. So Larry, thank you very much. I Git R Dune each day!!

reviewText: In fact, if it wasn't for the fact that the rental place had nothing good left on a Saturday night, I might have never seen this. I rented this and Artie Lang's comedy DVD. I watched Artie's first, it wasn't very funny. I was all prepared to watch another lame stand-up routine, when I started laughing within the first minute of Larry's DVD. I laughed out loud about 40 times, and it is NOT easy to make me laugh. This is one of the better comedy routines I have ever seen (Chris Rock is #1), and I would DEFINITELY recommend this if you are a comedy fan. This is MUCH funnier than it might seem (it looked pretty dumb to me when I rented it). Give it a try, you won't be disappointed. On a side note, for dumb parents who think its a slang sex term: Git-R-Done can mean anything, like if your friend says "I'm going to the store for more root beer" you can reply "Git-R-Done!". Its NOT solely a sexual term (although it can be used that way).
